We use the recurrence 
$$\Gamma_q(z+1)=[z]_q\,\Gamma_q(z),\qquad [z]_q=\frac{1-q^z}{1-q}.$$
We set 
$$S=\prod_{k=0}^{1}\frac{\Gamma_q\bigl(\tfrac12+4k\bigr)\,\Gamma_q\bigl(\tfrac12+4k+2\bigr)}
{\Gamma_q\bigl(\tfrac12+4k+1\bigr)\,\Gamma_q\bigl(\tfrac12+4k+3\bigr)}=F(0)\,F(1).$$

k=0:
$$F(0)=\frac{\Gamma_q(\tfrac12)\,\Gamma_q(\tfrac52)}{\Gamma_q(\tfrac32)\,\Gamma_q(\tfrac72)}.$$
Using
$$\Gamma_q(\tfrac32)=[\tfrac12]_q\Gamma_q(\tfrac12),\;
\Gamma_q(\tfrac52)=[\tfrac32]_q\Gamma_q(\tfrac32),\;
\Gamma_q(\tfrac72)=[\tfrac52]_q\Gamma_q(\tfrac52),$$
one finds
$$F(0)=\frac{1}{[\tfrac12]_q\,[\tfrac52]_q}
=\frac{(1-q)^2}{(1-q^{1/2})(1-q^{5/2})}.$$

k=1:
$$F(1)=\frac{\Gamma_q(\tfrac92)\,\Gamma_q(\tfrac{13}2)}
{\Gamma_q(\tfrac{11}2)\,\Gamma_q(\tfrac{15}2)}
=\frac{1}{[\tfrac92]_q\,[\tfrac{13}2]_q}
=\frac{(1-q)^2}{(1-q^{9/2})(1-q^{13/2})}.$$

Hence
$$S=F(0)\,F(1)
=\frac{(1-q)^4}{(1-q^{1/2})(1-q^{5/2})(1-q^{9/2})(1-q^{13/2})}.$$
